      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And Sheba.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Some would translate here, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "or",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Sheba (see below). No doubt the city, of which nothing further is known, derived its name from Beer-sheba, \"the well of the oath,\" close by. It is true that some little difficulty is caused by the omission of this city in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 4:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", by the identification of Shehah with Beer-sheba in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 26:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and by the fact that in ver. 6 we are told that there were thirteen cities in this catalogue, whereas there are fourteen. On the other hand, Keil has remarked that in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 15:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the number of names does not correspond to the whole number of cities given; and we have a Shema, probably a mistake for Sheba, in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 15:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", mentioned before Moladah among the cities of Judah. And, lastly, we have very few instances in Scripture of the disjunctive use of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "ו",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", though it seems impossible to deny that it is used in this sense in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 18:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Joshua 19:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
